        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-24 19:36:22.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nQuestion, Liam, is there a reason to use Parameter*Exception classes, instead of reusing the unchecked java.lang.IllegalArgumentException?",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "4a6141908d44ac1b7fb199380b8c180dc4b59502",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2787,
          "name": "Liam Fallon",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
          "username": "liamfallon"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-24 19:39:22.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nThe reason as so that this exception could be specialized if you wanted to have a specific exception for a particular type of parameter exception. Also sometimes this exception can be thrown when say parameter values are correct but are in an illegal combination, for example if you had stream and file output and someone specified a coreect stream parameter and value but on a file outputter.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "3b9009004c85d9c093e48666434d4693f44858ed",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 477,
          "name": "Jorge Hernandez",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jorge.hernandez-herrero@att.com",
          "username": "jhh"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-24 20:58:42.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nOK, thanks Liam.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "3206a80854f1be3ee4063ab1d5b15ac96e55b5a2",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2787,
          "name": "Liam Fallon",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
          "username": "liamfallon"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-25 08:47:50.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n@Jim Hahn, I had a look at the SystemPersistence class. That's an Interface/class (with FileSystemPersistence) for reading in and handling Java properties in one place. I have to admit to developing a dislike of Java properties over the years for many reasons, chief among which are:\n1) They are not typed, causing parameter checking to be peppered all through the code where they are used\n2) They cannot be validated against a schema so you cannot systematically structure or group parameters.\n\nThe @Property annotation approach is cool, lets see if we can incorporate that in.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
