      {
        "id": "f38978998e4bf9548d1a7949ff6b321105bb6224",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-25 12:58:19.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> @Jim Hahn, I had a look at the SystemPersistence class. That's an\n > Interface/class (with FileSystemPersistence) for reading in and\n > handling Java properties in one place. I have to admit to\n > developing a dislike of Java properties over the years for many\n > reasons, chief among which are:\n > 1) They are not typed, causing parameter checking to be peppered\n > all through the code where they are used\n > 2) They cannot be validated against a schema so you cannot\n > systematically structure or group parameters.\n > \n > The @Property annotation approach is cool, lets see if we can\n > incorporate that in.\n\nYes, my other projects typically use XML property files type-checked via XSDs, but as Properties permeate the Policy project, it seemed appropriate to stick with that.  @Property provides the type safety and options checking, as well as validation of all properties up front, rather than waiting until a given property is actually requested.\n\nAny reply to my last comments on line 39 of AbstractParameters?  Is it necessary to pass the class at all - why not just use getClass() inside the constructor?",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "d2ea345acf5f8acc21baed1115f8a23e903cd565",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 2787,
          "name": "Liam Fallon",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "liam.fallon@est.tech",
          "username": "liamfallon"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-25 13:03:06.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\nI'm not proposing to change the current approach to properties in existing code, the common property handling should be used for new code (initially the SDC distributor) and also in APEX, which already uses an earlier version of this.\n\nI'll address your other comment separately.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
      {
        "id": "7f1ae8c593f9e707085bcd5702088928bf2fbfb8",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2018-07-25 13:35:38.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 4:\n\n> I'm not proposing to change the current approach to properties in\n > existing code, the common property handling should be used for new\n > code (initially the SDC distributor) and also in APEX, which\n > already uses an earlier version of this.\n > \n > I'll address your other comment separately.\n\nNo problem - I wasn't suggesting this be changed in APEX, just providing more background on @Property.",
        "patchset_number": 4
      },
